.TH "TEMPORAL.ZONEDDATETIME.HOURSINDAY" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Temporal.ZonedDateTime.hoursInDay \-
Temporal.ZonedDateTime.prototype.hoursInDay
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]hoursInDay\f[B]\f[R] accessor property of
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] instances returns a positive integer
representing the number of hours in the day of this date in the time
zone.
It may be more or less than 24 in the case of offset changes such as
daylight saving time.
.PP
Because \f[CR]ZonedDateTime\f[R] is the only class that\(cqs time
zone\-aware, and hours in a day can only change by offset changes, all
other classes assume 24\-hour days.
.PP
The set accessor of \f[CR]hoursInDay\f[R] is \f[CR]undefined\f[R].
You cannot change this property directly.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Using hoursInDay
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] dt = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq2024\-03\-10T01:58:00\-05:00[America/New_York]\(dq,
);
console.log(dt.hoursInDay); \f[I]// 23; this is the day of transition into DST\f[R]

\f[B]const\f[R] dt2 = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq2024\-11\-03T01:58:00\-04:00[America/New_York]\(dq,
);
console.log(dt2.hoursInDay); \f[I]// 25; this is the day of transition out of DST\f[R]

\f[B]const\f[R] dt3 = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq2024\-11\-04T01:58:00\-05:00[America/New_York]\(dq,
);
console.log(dt3.hoursInDay); \f[I]// 24\f[R]
.EE
